The points $P_5$ and $P_6$ can be located at the intersections of the $m(r)$ (blue) curve with $m=-r-1$ (red) line. The point $P_6$ is located at $m\sim 1.54$ and $r  \simeq -2.54$ with $x\simeq 0.48$. As $m(r\simeq-2.54) >1$, the point $P_6$ is an unstable point. Point $P_5$ represents the saddle matter era. The condition for $P_5$ to exist is $m (r=-1)=0$. It is shown in \cite{Kruglov:2013qaa} that the point $P_5$ is situated at $x=\beta R\sim 0$. But, saddle matter point has to be at higher curvature than the de Sitter point $P_1$ to explain the cosmic history correctly. Moreover, $dm/dr$ at $P_5$ has to be greater than $-1$ for the existence of acceptable saddle matter era. From the definitions of $m$ and $r$ and Eq.\eqref{model}, one can obtain the expression of $m'(r)$ \cite{Kruglov:2013qaa}. 
